s for metastatic spread.\n    * **Bronchoscopy with biopsy:** To obtain tissue for definitive diagnosis and molecular testing (e.g., EGFR, ALK mutations).\n    * **PET scan:** To further assess for metastatic disease.\n    * **Blood tests:** To evaluate for other potential causes of the symptoms and monitor organ function.\n\nGiven the strong suspicion of lung cancer, referral to an oncologist for MDT discussion and treatment planning is paramount.  Management will depend on the staging of the disease and the patient's performance status.  Multidisciplinary input from respiratory medicine, oncology, pathology, and radiology will be essential in developing a personalized treatment plan.  The comorbidities will need careful consideration when choosing treatment modalities to minimize potential complications and interactions.  Patient education and psychosocial support will be crucial throughout the treatment process.\n\n**Limitations and Uncertainties:** The diagnosis of lung cancer remains presumptive until confirmed by biopsy.  The severity of the comorbidities and their impact on treatment will become clearer with further investigations and assessment.  The patient's true performance status requires formal evaluation.",
