on the current imaging findings and may be subject to change following histopathological confirmation and further clinical staging investigations.  The size measurements are derived from the CT chest.\n\n**Progression Criteria:**  No prior imaging for comparison to assess progression.\n\n**4. Anatomical Considerations:**\n\nThe primary lesion is located in the right upper lobe, close to the hilum, with involvement of the right hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes.  The proximity of the primary tumor to the mediastinum and the presence of mediastinal adenopathy are crucial factors influencing treatment strategy.  The supraclavicular lymphadenopathy noted on physical exam needs further investigation with imaging (e.g., ultrasound with biopsy) to determine if it represents metastatic spread or reactive lymphadenopathy.\n\n**5. Recommendations for Additional Imaging:**\n\nWhile the current imaging provides a strong indication of Stage IIIA lung cancer, definitive diagnosis requires tissue confirmation.  Therefore, the following are recommended:\n\n* **Bronchoscopy with Bronchoalveolar Lavage (BAL) and Biopsy:**  To obtain tissue samples for histopathological examination, including immunohistochemistry to determine the specific subtype of non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC).\n* **Endobronchial Ultrasound-guided transbronchial needle aspiration (EBUS-TBNA) or Mediastinoscopy/Thoracoscopy:** To obtain tissue samples from the mediastinal lymph nodes for confirmation of nodal involvement and to potentially help guide treatment decisions.\n* **Ultrasound-guided fine-needle aspiration (FNAC) of the right supraclavicular lymph node:** To evaluate the supraclavicular lymph node for potential metastatic disease.\n\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nThe imaging findings strongly suggest a Stage IIIA NSCLC.  However, histopathological confirmation is crucial for definitive diagnosis and treatment planning. A multidisciplinary team (MDT) meeting is recommended to discuss the findings and formulate a