ia:**  No prior imaging for comparison.\n\n\n**4. Anatomical Considerations:**\n\nThe primary lesion is located in the right upper lobe, close to the hilum.  The involvement of hilar and mediastinal lymph nodes suggests local spread. The relationship to major vessels and bronchi requires further assessment with higher-resolution imaging if needed (e.g., endobronchial ultrasound).\n\n**5. Recommendations for Additional Imaging (if needed):**\n\nWhile the current imaging provides a strong basis for staging, the following may be considered depending on the clinical context and planned treatment:\n\n* **Endobronchial Ultrasound (EBUS) or Mediastinoscopy:** To confirm or exclude mediastinal lymph node involvement and obtain tissue samples for further pathological analysis.  This is crucial for precise N staging and treatment planning.\n\n* **Further Imaging of Supraclavicular Nodes:** If clinically significant, further imaging of the supraclavicular lymph nodes (e.g., ultrasound with biopsy) may be warranted to evaluate for potential N3 involvement.\n\n* **Brain MRI:** Although there is currently no evidence of distant metastases, a brain MRI may be considered in the future, particularly if systemic treatment is planned.\n\n\n**Limitations and Uncertainties:**\n\nThis imaging report is based solely on the provided imaging studies and clinical information.  Histopathological confirmation is essential for a definitive diagnosis and to determine the specific subtype of non-small cell lung cancer. The absence of prior imaging limits the assessment of disease progression. The clinical stage may be refined after further investigations (EBUS/mediastinoscopy, biopsy) and pathological analysis.  The report should be considered in conjunction with the complete clinical picture and other diagnostic findings.  A multidisciplinary team approach is crucial for optimal patient management.",
