      "markdown_content": "# Pathology Report\n\n## Specimen Details\n- **Type:** Right upper lobe mass biopsy obtained via bronchoscopy.\n- **Adequacy:** Adequate tissue for histological examination and molecular testing was received.  Multiple tissue fragments were present, allowing for representative sampling.\n- **Processing notes:** Standard formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded (FFPE) processing was performed.  Slides were prepared for hematoxylin and eosin (H&E) staining and immunohistochemistry (IHC).  DNA was extracted for molecular testing.\n- **Quality indicators:**  Tissue morphology was well-preserved.  Sufficient high-quality DNA was extracted for reliable molecular testing.\n\n## Microscopic Findings\n1. **Histological Features**\n   - **Type:** Adenocarcinoma of the lung.  The tumor cells exhibit glandular differentiation with formation of tubules and acini.  Cytological features include moderate nuclear pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and moderate amounts of eosinophilic cytoplasm.\n   - **Grade:**  Grade 2 (moderate differentiation).  This is based on the degree of nuclear pleomorphism, the presence of mitotic figures, and the architectural pattern of the tumor.  More detailed grading may require additional sections or ancillary studies.\n   - **Special features:** No evidence of mucinous or squamous differentiation was observed.  The tumor shows evidence of invasion into the surrounding lung parenchyma.  Lymphovascular invasion was not identified in this sample, but this cannot be excluded definitively without examining additional sections.\n   - **Prognostic factors:**  High PD-L1 expression (80%) is a favorable prognostic factor, suggesting potential responsiveness to immunotherapy.  The presence of KRAS G12C mutation is a less favourable prognostic factor, indicating that immunotherapy may be limited in efficacy.  Further staging is required to determine the overall prognosis.\n\n2. **Molecular Results**\n   - **Mutation status:** KRAS G12C mutation detected.  EGFR, ALK, and ROS1 were wild-type.\n   - **Biomarker levels:** PD-L1 expression: 80%.  This indicates high expression and suggests potential benefit from PD-1/PD-L1 inhibitors.\n   - **Therapeutic targets:** The KRAS G12C mutation is a therapeutic target for specific tyrosine kinase inhibitors (e.g., sotorasib, adagrasib). The high PD-L1 expression suggests potential benefit from immunotherapy (e.g., pembrolizumab, atezolizumab).\n\n\n## Clinical Implications\n- **Treatment relevance:** The KRAS G12C mutation and high PD-L1 expression significantly influence treatment decisions.  Targeted therapy with a KRAS G12C inhibitor and/or immunotherapy are viable options.  The presence of comorbidities (diabetes and hypertension) needs to be considered when choosing the treatment regimen.\n- **Prognostic factors:**  The stage of the disease (Stage IIIA, based on imaging) is a crucial prognostic factor.  The high PD-L1 expression is a positive prognostic indicator, but the presence of the KRAS mutation might somewhat mitigate that.  The patient's age and performance status will also be important factors in determining the prognosis and treatment plan.\n- **Additional testing needs:**  Further evaluation is needed to confirm the absence of lymphovascular invasion.  Comprehensive lymph node assessment (e.g., via EBUS-TBNA) is crucial for accurate staging and treatment planning.  Additional tissue samples from involved lymph nodes would help to confirm the presence of metastatic disease.  Further testing for other potentially targetable mutations (e.g., comprehensive genomic profiling or next-generation sequencing) could identify additional treatment options.  A detailed assessment of the patient's performance status is also necessary.",
